      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Base Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":328,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":308,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the relaxed end of easy pace — 5:53/km or slower. Let your body wake up, no rushing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":328,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic rhythm. Conversational effort — you should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a gentle jog. Use this time to tune into how your body feels after the effort.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of brisk walking and dynamic leg swings before you start the clock. This matters especially on Monday when your body is coming off the weekend long run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5–10 minutes of gentle walking and static stretching — calves, hip flexors, and quads. No rush.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your bread-and-butter aerobic run. Based on your Daniels-Gilbert zones, easy runs should sit between 5:08 and 5:53 per km — the goal here is aerobic stimulus without accumulated fatigue. At 60 km per week you have a strong base, and these runs are the quiet infrastructure that makes everything else work. Resist the urge to drift faster; the physiological benefit comes from the sustained aerobic load, not the speed.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Marathon Pace Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":14,\"target_duration_minutes\":72,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":328,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":272,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"20 minutes easy, building gradually from your slowest easy pace toward the middle of the easy zone. Include 4 x 20-second strides at the end to prime your neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":272,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"3 x 12 minutes at marathon pace (4:32/km). This is your goal race pace — it should feel controlled and demanding but sustainable. Think: focused, not frantic.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"3 minutes easy jog between each marathon-pace rep. Use these recoveries — don't walk, keep moving and let your breathing settle.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog back to full recovery. Check in with your legs — any tightness worth noting for tomorrow?\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Warm up for at least 15 minutes easy before touching marathon pace. Your body needs time to reach the right physiological state — skipping this increases injury risk and makes the workout feel much harder than it needs to.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy cooldown jog followed by dynamic hip and hamstring stretches. Hydrate well — this is a glycogen-burning session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Marathon pace work is the cornerstone of your 3:15 build. Your target marathon pace from your Daniels-Gilbert zones is 4:32/km — this session makes that pace feel familiar and controlled rather than alien on race day. Three cruise intervals at marathon pace, separated by short recovery jogs, trains your body to clear lactate efficiently at goal effort. The total marathon-pace volume here (36 minutes) is appropriately modest for this early phase of your build. You'll revisit this format regularly, progressively lengthening the work intervals over the coming weeks.\",\"perceived_effort\":6},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":328,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":236,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"A full 20-minute easy warmup is non-negotiable before interval work. Include 6 x 20-second accelerations (strides) in the final 5 minutes to prime your legs for the faster running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":236,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 5 minutes at interval pace (3:56/km). This is hard — a 9 or 9.5 out of 10. You should reach a point where conversation becomes impossible. Hold form: tall posture, relaxed shoulders, quick cadence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 minutes easy jog between each interval. Walk the first 60 seconds if needed — the goal is enough recovery to hit the next rep at full quality, not to minimize rest.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy jog. Slow is fine here — the only goal is flushing the legs and bringing HR down gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Do not skip or shorten the warmup on interval days. A full 20 minutes easy plus strides prepares your cardiovascular system and reduces the shock of jumping to 3:56/km.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 15 minutes easy jog. Follow with calf stretches and hip flexor lengthening. Eat within 30 minutes to begin recovery.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are where you build your aerobic ceiling — the upper limit that determines how fast you can ultimately run. Your Daniels-Gilbert zone interval pace is 3:56/km. For a 3:15 marathoner, having a well-developed VO2max is essential because it gives you a larger aerobic reserve to draw on at marathon pace, making 4:32/km feel more manageable. Five-minute intervals are a classic, effective format — long enough to stress the system meaningfully, short enough to repeat with quality. One interval day per week is intentional given your 4-day schedule; this keeps the stimulus high and the risk of accumulated fatigue low.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":148,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":338,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":272,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin at your slowest comfortable easy pace — 5:50–5:53/km. No pressure to move up the pace range early. Let the first 15–20 minutes just be a stroll that happens to be running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":105,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy aerobic running. Aim for the middle of your easy range (5:20–5:35/km) once you're warmed up. This is your biggest aerobic stimulus of the week — protect it by not going out too fast.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":272,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4–5 km at marathon pace (4:32/km). This teaches your legs to find race pace on tired muscles — one of the most race-specific adaptations in marathon training. Push through the discomfort; this is meant to be hard at the end of a long run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Bring it home easy. Walk the last 2–3 minutes if you need to. You earned it.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"On long run days, a 5-minute walk before you start running is highly worthwhile — especially on Sunday mornings. Let the body ease in. No strides, no drills — just walking, then easy running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5–10 minutes after finishing. Prioritize hydration and eating within 45 minutes. Light stretching — don't force anything while fatigued. Consider a short nap or legs-up-the-wall for 10 minutes if your schedule allows.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your long run is the anchor of your marathon training week. At 26 km this week, you're continuing a strong trajectory — your training history shows 22, 24, and 26 km long runs across recent weeks, which is excellent. The marathon-pace finish (final 4–5 km at 4:32/km) is a deliberate stress: it teaches your body to sustain goal pace when glycogen is depleted and legs are fatigued, which is exactly the condition you'll face at km 35 of the race. This format, drawn from Daniels-Gilbert zone principles, is more race-specific than simply running a flat easy 26 km. Your total weekly volume this week sits at approximately 64 km — a modest 3–7% step up from recent weeks, well within safe progression. Fuel before this run and plan to carry water or plan your route around water access.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
